M1 and the monetary base

The data is available at the Sistema Gerenciador de Séries Temporais (SGS) do Banco Central.

We are going to use the average of the period, for both monetary base as well as M1. As deflator, we are going to use the last available IPCA index. The R package used to download the data directly from the Central Bank is called BETS.

  • BM - Base monetária restrita (média nos dias úteis do mês)
    • Unity: u.m.c. (mil)
    • Periodicity: Mensal
    • Serie number: 1785
    • Start date: 31/01/1980
    • Last available date (in 25/08/2018): 30/06/2018
  • Meios de pagamento - M1 (média nos dias úteis do mês)
    • Unity: u.m.c. (mil)
    • Periodicity: Mensal
    • Serie number: 1824
    • Start date: 31/01/1980
    • Last available date (consultado em 25/08/2018): 30/06/2018
  • Índice nacional de preços ao consumidor-amplo (IPCA)
    • Unity: Var % mensal
    • Periodicity: Mensal
    • Serie number: 1824
    • Start date: 02/01/1980
    • Last available date (consultado em 25/08/2018): 31/07/2018
# Algumas variáveis auxiliares de datas, assim não precisamos alterar o código inteiro depois
# Eu recomendo sempre usar uma data de fim única, pois algumas variáveis demoram mais para ser atualizadas do que outras
inicio_82 <- "1982-01-01"
inicio_95 <- "1995-01-01" # Estou usando isso para cortar as séries posteriormente
inicio_96 <- "1996-01-01"
fim       <- "2018-06-30"
ano <- as.numeric(substr(inicio_82, start = 1, stop = 4))
mes <- as.numeric(substr(inicio_82, start = 6, stop = 7))
dia <- as.numeric(substr(inicio_82, start = 9, stop = 10))

M1   <- BETS.get("1824", from = inicio_82, to = fim)
BM   <- BETS.get("1785", from = inicio_82, to = fim)
IPCA <- BETS.get("433",  from = inicio_82, to = fim)

# Agora preciso converter os valores de M1 e BM para reais
# Peguei aqui: http://diniznumismatica.blogspot.com.br/2017/10/converter-outros-padroes-monetarios-em.html
# Cruzeiro Novo (de 01/02/1967 até 28/02/1986)
# Faça a divisão por 1000^3 * 2750
M1_1 <- window(M1, c(1982,01), c(1986,02))/((1000^3)*2750)
BM_1 <- window(BM, c(1982,01), c(1986,02))/((1000^3)*2750)

# Cruzado (de 01/03/1986 até 31/01/1989)
# Faça a divisão por 1000^2 * 2750
M1_2 <- window(M1, c(1986,03), c(1989,01))/((1000^2)*2750)
BM_2 <- window(BM, c(1986,03), c(1989,01))/((1000^2)*2750)

# Cruzado Novo e Cruzeiro (01/02/1989 a 31/07/1993)
# Faça a divisão por 1000*2750
M1_3 <- window(M1, c(1989,02), c(1993,07))/(1000*2750)
BM_3 <- window(BM, c(1989,02), c(1993,07))/(1000*2750)

# Cruzeiro real (01/08/1993 a 30/06/1994)
# Faça a divisão por 2750
M1_4 <- window(M1, c(1993,08), c(1994,06))/(2750)
BM_4 <- window(BM, c(1993,08), c(1994,06))/(2750)

# Último pedaço - plano real
M1_5 <- window(M1, c(1994,07))
BM_5 <- window(BM, c(1994,07))

comb <- ts.union(M1_1, M1_2, M1_3, M1_4, M1_5)
M1_final <- pmin(comb[,1], comb[,2], comb[,3], comb[,4], comb[,5], na.rm = TRUE)

comb <- ts.union(BM_1, BM_2, BM_3, BM_4, BM_5)
BM_final <- pmin(comb[,1], comb[,2], comb[,3], comb[,4], comb[,5], na.rm = TRUE)

# Agora vou trabalhar com o deflator. Usei a metodologia do IPEA http://www.ipeadata.gov.br/iframe_transformacao.aspx?width=1474&height=701
ipca2 <- IPCA # Salvo em uma nova variável só pro caso de dar errado não ter que baixar os dados de novo
ipca2[1] <- 100 # Primeiro faço o primeiro valor ser a base e depois mudo de base porque eu aprendi assim

# Transforma em índice
for (i in 2:length(ipca2)){
  ipca2[i] <- round(ipca2[(i-1)]*(1+ipca2[(i)]/100),2)
}

# Média geométrica
for (i in 1:(length(ipca2)-1)){
  ipca2[i] <- sqrt(ipca2[i]*ipca2[(i+1)])
}

# Muda a base para o último valor
for (i in 1:length(ipca2)) {
  ipca2[i] <- tail(ipca2, n=1)/ipca2[i]
}

ipca2 <- ts(ipca2,  start = c(ano, mes, dia), frequency = 12) # Converte para série temporal

# Deflaciona M1 e BM
M1_def <- M1_final * ipca2
BM_def <- BM_final * ipca2

First graph starts in Jan/1995 (6 months after the currency stabilization). Since we are analyzing the currency demand, we a using the average series (the series measured in the end of the month is most suitable to analyze the public accounts, due to seigniorage).

The break observed in the graph, where it changes its behavior in 1997, is due to the creation of CPMF (in Jan 23rd, 1997). Since this tax is over the cashdraws, people are going less to the bank or they are not going to make deposits at all. In 1999 it was extinct for 6 months (Jan-Jun) and was finally extinct in Jan/2008. With the CPMF ending, people started to reduce their cash retention.

As for Jan/2003, there was a raise in the interest rate to counter the raise in the exchange rate, which ocurred in response to the new elected president. Remember: when interest rates go up, the demand for money goes down.

In this next graph we have the whole period. In 1994 with the implementation of the Plano Real we have a an abrupt increase in the demand for money, pushed by the economy stabilization.

From Jan/82 to 1986 we had the hyperinflation period, which, throught the Fisher channel, increased the interest rate: people spent all their money in the beginning of the month and didn’t demand money. The two other lines after 86 are the Plano Bresse and Plano Verão.

Also in 1986, there was the Plano Cruzado, where a change in the multiplier made things strange. Prices were frozen in February, impacting the economy. The financial application return dropped from 20% to 0.6% per month. Knowing about the decrease in interest rates, people started to demand money, which increased the PMPP and deposits in cash. People who received money simply didn’t deposited in the bank, because the return was ridiculous and people whose money was in the bank didn’t bother to change to another financial applications. With all this money available, banks started to increase credit supply by further diminishing the interest rates. This led to a increase in the money supply in the economy, which, by its turn, increased consumption (aggregate demand increased). The productive capacity stayed the same, but they couldn’t raise prices (they were frozen!), leading tp scarcity. This would be prevented with the central bank had raised the compulsory transfers from the commercial banks (in fact, this was one of the policies in the implementarion of the Real currency in 1994).

Money multiplier

Now we are going to take a look into the money multiplier, given by M1/BM. In 1994, to avoid an increase in the multiplier motivated by the lower inflation, the Central Bank altered the compulsory deposits, making the multiplier shrink. As for 2002, due to the uncertainty in the elections, it was necessary to raise the interest rates (contractionary policy to counter inflation).

Estimating the money demand

Getting the data

We are going to try to explain the money demand \(m_t\) (here assumed equal to \(M_1\)) using GDP and interest rates. Due to time constraints, I’m going to take the first difference of the series in logs, to remove any trends. The following variables can be used:

  • Taxa de Juros - Selic (Interest Rate)
    • Beginning of the series: July, 1986.
    • End of the series: April, 2018.
    • Unity: % monthly.
    • Series number in SGS: 4390.
    • Source: Brazil’s Central Bank - Open Market Operations Department (BCB-Demab).
  • Monthly GDP
    • Beginning of the series: January, 1990.
    • End of the series: February, 2018.
    • Unity: Brazilian Real (R$) - millions.
    • Series number in SGS: 4380
    • Source: Brazil’s Central Bank - Economic Department (BCB-Depec).
    • Obs: O PIB mensal é um indicador mensal produzido pelo Banco Central do Brasil (BCB) para utilização no cálculo da relação entre agregados econômicos mensais (como dívida pública, saldo em transações correntes e saldo de crédito) e o PIB. Isto é feito porque o PIB, oficialmente calculado no Brasil pelo IBGE, é divulgado apenas em frequência trimestral, diferentemente de várias informações econômicas compiladas pelo Banco Central, como as citadas acima. Note que não se trata de cálculo do PIB a partir de informações primárias, mas apenas de uma estimativa que é feita via interpolação dos valores trimestrais já divulgados ou dos projetados.

I’m just going do download everything again to have all variables in the same dates.

# Click here to see the how the qs statistics is calculated: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/148573/the-results-and-specifics-from-the-qs-function-in-r
# The first 7 results are related to the whole series, the last 7 comprehends only the last 8 years
# qsori is the original series
# qsorievadj is the original series corrected for extreme values
# qsrsd is the residual's series of the ARIMA model
# qssadj is the series with seasonal adjustment 
# qssadjevadj is the series with seasonal adjustment corrected for extreme values
# qsirr is the series of the irregular component
# qsirrevadj is the series of the irregular component corrected for extreme values
# by the output, we can conclude that there is no evidence of seasonal components in the adjusted series, the residuals and the irregular component, even when we look just the last 8 years.

Fitting a TVP-VAR

Since we observed some changes in the volatility, could be the case that we are dealing with multivariate stochastic volatility. Moreover, a 20 years span is a lot and it is probable that the VAR coefficients changed through time.

Funções impulso resposta

Peguei a explicação daqui daqui: A FIR estima o impacto de um choque unitário em algum elemento de \(\varepsilon_t\). Os elementos de \(c_t\), \(B_{j,t}\) e \(A_t\) em (1) são mantidos fixos em seus valores em \(t\), mas os elementos de \(\Sigma_t\) são substituídos pela média de todos os períodos. Note que a ordem das variáveis importa e deve ser justificada por argumentos econômicos. As FIR contém os percentis 5, 25, 50, 75 e 95.
